# Count Zig-Zag Arrays

## 📌 Problem Statement

Given:

* An integer `n` representing the length of the array.
* A range `[l, r]` from which each element can be chosen.

Count the number of arrays of length `n` such that:

* Every element belongs to the range `[l, r]`.
* Adjacent elements alternate between increasing and decreasing.

In other words, the array forms a **zig-zag pattern**:

```text
a0 < a1 > a2 < a3 > ...
```

or

```text
a0 > a1 < a2 > a3 < ...
```

Return the count modulo:

```text
1,000,000,007
```

---

## 🧠 Approach

### Dynamic Programming

Let:

```text
m = r - l + 1
```

Since only relative ordering matters, values can be compressed into:

```text
0, 1, 2, ..., m-1
```

---

### DP Definition

Let:

```text
dp[x]
```

represent the number of valid zig-zag sequences ending with value `x`.

Initially, for arrays of length `1`:

```text
dp[x] = 1
```

for every possible value.

---

### Transition

At position `i`:

* If we need an increasing relation:

```text
previous < current
```

then:

```text
dp[current] =
Σ dp[previous]
(previous < current)
```

* If we need a decreasing relation:

```text
previous > current
```

then:

```text
dp[current] =
Σ dp[previous]
(previous > current)
```

---

### Prefix/Suffix Sum Optimization

A direct transition would require:

```text
O(m²)
```

per position.

Instead:

* Traverse left-to-right for one direction.
* Traverse right-to-left for the other direction.
* Maintain cumulative sums.

This reduces each DP layer to:

```text
O(m)
```

---

### Alternating Directions

For each position:

```text
i odd  → increasing
i even → decreasing
```

(or vice versa depending on indexing).

The implementation alternates the sweep direction using:

```cpp
bool dir = i & 1;
```

---

### Final Answer

The DP computes one zig-zag orientation.

Since both patterns are valid:

```text
< > < > ...
```

and

```text
> < > < ...
```

the final result is:

```text
2 × total_sequences
```

taken modulo `1e9 + 7`.

---

## 💻 Code (C++)

```cpp
constexpr int P = 1e9 + 7, N = 2000;

using ll = long long;

static ll dp[N];

class Solution {
public:
    static int zigZagArrays(int n, int l, int r) {
        const int m = r - l + 1;

        fill_n(dp, m, 1);

        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            const bool dir = i & 1;

            ll Sum = 0;

            const int i0 = (-dir & m - 1);
            const int iN = (-!dir & m + 1) - 1;
            const int step = 1 - (dir << 1);

            for (int j = i0; j != iN; j += step) {
                ll x = dp[j];
                dp[j] = Sum;
                Sum = (Sum + x) % P;
            }
        }

        return 2 * reduce(dp, dp + m, 0LL) % P;
    }
};

auto init = []() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cout.tie(nullptr);
    return 'c';
}();
```

